AGI -&nbsp;Ukraine cashed out the billion US aids that long demanded Congress, but lost ground in front of the Russian advance in Dometsk oblast. Moscow has announced that its forces have gained territory near the key city of the Chasiv Yar battlefield, highlighting the pressure it faces Zelensky while preparing to receive $61 billion in new aids.
<br> After months of intestine struggles, the U.S. Chamber finally approved the important package giving a much less moral boost to Ukrainian forces forced on the defensive. The package still needs to be approved by the Senate before Joe Biden can make the final clearance, but the outcome of the vote in the high room is discounted. Zelensky urged the United States to ensure that aids arrive at destination quickly.
"It is very important for us to have a prompt Senate decision in support of the Ukrainian package," he wrote on his social media. And in his evening speech he added: "The time between political decisions and the actual destruction of the enemy to the forehead should be as short as possible."
<br Analysts have warned that it will take some time before Kiev can perceive the benefits of the aid package, which includes 14 billion dollars to train and equip the Ukrainian army. Only once the bill passes to the Senate and will be approved by Biden will begin the long transfer process in the country devastated by the war. Moscow has tried to minimize the impact of new aids by claiming that they do nothing but "crowd" even more Washington in the war.
"February attempts to save Zelensky's neo-Nazi regime are destined for failure," said Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Maria Zakharova.&nbsp;
However for Kiev the situation on the field continues to deteriorate even if Russia, which claimed the capture of Bogdanivka, a small village on the front line less than three kilometers north-east of Chasiv Yar, undergoes a new smack in the Black Sea, where the new ship was hit. Kiev has often tested the ability of the Russian Navy to defend its fleet with attacks that humiliated the Kremlin and forced it to move the ships away from the annexed Crimean Peninsula.
&nbsp;
"Another bad day for the Black Sea Russian fleet," said the Ukrainian Ministry of Defense, announcing that its navy attacked the rescue ship "Kommuna", used for deep-water work, including lifting submarines and sinking cargos. The Ukrainian Navy spokesman Dmytro Pletenchuk said that the damage caused by the attack is not clear but that the ship "is no longer able to carry out its tasks". The governor of Sebastopoli settled by Russia, Mikhail Razvozhayev, did not confirm that "Kommuna" was hit, but said that the Moscow army "rejected an attack with an anti-ship missile" on a ship in the port, and that the fall of debris caused a fire.&nbsp;

